ding being a basis for the transatlantic slave trade. Offering examples of how attitudes about skin color differ in the U.S., Brazil, India, and South Africa, Jablonski suggests that a knowledge of the evolution and social importance of skin color can help eliminate color-based discrimination and racism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aHuman skin colorvCross-cultural studies. 0aHuman skin colorxPhysiological aspects. 0aHuman skin colorxSocial aspects. 0aHuman skin color. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  abiological traits.  abiology of skin color.  abrazil.  acolor based discrimination.  adark skin.  aevolution and culture.  aglobal history.  ahistory of skin color.  ahuman evolution.  aillustrated.  aindia.  amelanin pigment.  amigrations.  aprehistory.  aracism.  askin color and environment.  askin color.  askin pigmentation.  aslave trade.  asocial differences.  asocial historians.  asocial history.  asocial interactions.  asocial meaning.  asocial sciences.  asouth africa.  astereotypes.  aunited states.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052025153340uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095377240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520953772423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520953772/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY